The plant 

Dryopteris atrata
(Wall. Ex Kunze) Ching

, which belongs to the 
Dryopteridaceae
family, is widely distributed in the southern provinces adjacent to the Yangtze River in 
China
(Editorial 

). Its rhizome can be used for treating ascariasis, paediatric worms, and functional uterine bleeding (

). Phloroglucinol derivatives are the characteristic constituents (

) as well as the principal active substances of 

Dryopteris

that display anthelmintic (

), antitumour (

), antimicrobial (

), antiviral (

), and antioxidant (

) activities. Furthermore, with more structurally interesting phloroglucinol derivatives identified from 

Dryopteris

(

, 

; 

; 

)—in particular, some adducts from 

Dryopteris wallichiana
(Spreng.) Hyl. Showing

unambiguous inhibitory activity against SARS-CoV-2 (

)—the phloroglucinol derivatives of 

Dryopteris

have drawn the attention of the research community.

Dryatraol A ( 1 ) had a molecular formula of C 26 H 34 O 5 as deduced by high-resolution electrospray ionisation mass spectrometry (HRESIMS) ( m/z 427.2476 [M + H] + , calculated for C 26 H 35 O 5 , 427.2479), suggestive of ten degrees of unsaturation. The 1 H NMR spectrum ( Table 1 ) revealed six methyl groups [ δ H 2.05, 1.28, 1.22, 1.10 (each 3H, s), 0.99 (3H, d, J = 6.4 Hz), and 0.94 (3H, t, J = 7.4 Hz)], three olefinic protons [ δ H 6.13 (1H, d, J = 5.2 Hz), 6.06 (1H, dd, J = 9.7, 5.2 Hz), and 5.88 (1H, dd, J = 9.7, 6.6 Hz)], and a hydrogen-bonded hydroxyl proton [ δ H 13.60 (1H, s)]. The 13 C NMR data ( Table 1 ) with the aid of HSQC and DEPT experiments displayed twenty-six carbon signals for six methyl, three methylene, seven methine, and ten non-protonated carbons. The above data implied that 1 might be a phloroglucinol-sesquiterpene adduct (
;
).

The assignment of the phloroglucinol ( 1.1 ) and sesquiterpene ( 1.2 ) moieties was further confirmed by interpretation of the 1D and 2D NMR spectra. The 13 C NMR data of fragment 1.1 were similar to those of the phloroglucinol unit in jejuguajavone I (
), which were further determined by the 1 H– 1 H COSY and HMBC correlations shown in Fig. 2 . The 1D NMR signals for fragment 1.2 showed many similarities to those of rulepidanol (
), and the main difference was that the two methylene carbons at δ C 32.4 (C-1) and δ C 24.7 (C-2) in rulepidanol were replaced by two methine carbons at δ C 87.7 (C-1 ′ ), 38.2 (C-2 ′ ) in 1 . This conclusion was verified by the spin system from H-1’ ( δ H 5.00) to H-4’ ( δ H 2.59) in the 1 H– 1 H COSY spectrum, as well as the HMBC correlations from H-1 ′ to C-3’ ( δ C 33.5)/C-5’ ( δ C 40.0)/C-9’ ( δ C 128.5)/C-10’ ( δ C 140.3). Additionally, the linkage between fragments 1.1 and 1.2 via the C-2 ′ –C-6 bond was deduced from the HMBC correlations from H-2’ ( δ H 3.18) to C-1 ( δ C 160.0)/C-6 ( δ C 110.8). Finally, an oxygen bridge between C-1 ′ and C-5 to form a furan ring was deduced from the downfield chemical shifts of C-5 ( δ C 156.1) and C-1’ ( δ C 87.7), as well as the remaining one degree of unsaturation.

The NMR data of the minor isomer 2b greatly resembled that of 2a , and a comprehensive interpretation showed that 2b had nearly the same structure as 2a . The main difference between 2a and 2b involved the signals assigned to fragment 2.1 ( δ C 163.8, 104.9, 158.8, 95.2, 162.4, 110.4 for C-1 C- 6 in 2a ; δ C 160.2, 106.1, 164.4, 95.9, 160.0, 108.9 for C-1 C- 6 in 2b ) (Figure S23, Supplementary data). These indicated that 2a and 2b were a pair of isomers formed by the rotation of the intramolecular hydrogen bond (
;
). Moreover, the key HMBC correlations between the hydrogen-bonded hydroxyl proton 3-OH ( δ H 13.65) and C-2 ( δ C 106.1)/C-3 ( δ C 164.4)/C-4 ( δ C 95.9) suggested that the intramolecular hydrogen bond in 2b was located between the 3-OH and C-7 ketone carbonyl, and that in 2a was formed between the 1-OH and C-7 ketone carbonyl, accordingly.

A careful review of the literature (

, 

; 

; 

; 

) indicates that the coupling patterns between phloroglucinols and terpenes from the 

Dryopteris

genus are via a pyran ring or a C–C single bond, no pattern of forming a furan ring has been discovered so far. Thus, in this study, a putative biosynthetic pathway of compound 
1,
which represented the first example of phloroglucinol-terpene adduct featuring an acylphloroglucinol motif fused with a rulepidanol-type sesquiterpene via a furan ring to form a 6/5/6/6 ring system, was proposed (Scheme S1, Supplementary data). First, the acylphloroglucinol motif 4-methylbutyrylphloroglucinol was derived from a Claisen reaction between butyryl-CoA and three molecules of malonyl-CoA, followed by methylation (

). Successive hydroxylation and dehydration of rulepidanol could lead to the formation of sesquiterpene intermediate 
v
. Finally, a radical coupling reaction between the acylphloroglucinol intermediate 
iii
and sesquiterpene intermediate 
v
generated compound 
1
(

).
